// README.txt -- ALP PISKIN & ANKIT KOTWAL

The std::cout in the program uses ANSI color codes in the terminal. (Had permission from the TA in the office hours)
Uses C++11 and the command is included in the makefile
IN COLOR:
Green X: Doodlebugs
Red O: Ants
Blank: NULL
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

SUMMARY:
- This project is intended to generate a simulation of a relationship between a predator(doodlebug) and a prey(ant) on a specified or
default size grid.

- The first class is Organism.
Organism class is an abstract class for Ant and Doodlebug and has virtual functions move() and breed() for the derived classes.
Organism contains a field that is of type Cell pointer so that it can refer to which cell in the grid it belongs to and set the Cell value
to a new value with setCell() when one of the derived classes call the function move().
Organism also has a  pure virtual getType() function that helps with separating the two derived classes

- The second class is Cell.
Cell class specifies the space reserved for each Organism (field: Organism pointer) on the grid. The constructor takes the relative position
of Cell with respect to the origin (first index) by x and y values. It also takes the pointer of the grid it belongs to so that it can refer to other
Cell objects in the Grid to call the getAdjacent() function. It also can setOrganism() the Organism pointer field it has to facilitate the move() functions
in similar ways to the setCell() function in the Organism.h

- The third class is Grid.
Grid.cpp contains a global function that creates a 2D vector of vectors. Initially, this function sets all Cells to NULL.
There are two constructors. The default constructor creates the grid with the default height and grid and sets the grid to its
data field in Grid class. The other constructor calls the createCells2d function by taking two size parameters. Data is the reference point of the grid that contains the Cells.
LoadGrid compares each getType() of Organism pointers inside each Cell and generates random indexes using rand() and modulo construction to randomly assign positions to Ants and
Doodlebugs. After a couple of getters and setters, run calls the whole move() and breed() functions of both Ant and Doodlebug classes in the assigned order.

- The fourth class is Ant.
Ant consists of two main functions: move() and breed(). The move() function of the Ant contains the same random rand() and modulo configuration used in the Grid to assign a new index
to move after calling the Cell it belongs to and gets the adjacent cells that are available. After adding unoccupied Cells to a vector, the function iterates over each and assigns a
random value (either -1 or 1 because it has to be up, left, right or down). The function also counts the move iteration and breeds after 3 moves if possible (uses bool can_move). Breed() kind of works
like a helper function to move as in it looks at the unoccupied cells and creates a new Ant at one of them in random. 

- The fifth class is Doodlebug.
Doodlebug consists of the same configuration as Ants with a few additions. To start with, Doodlebugs have different values for breeding and they also can starve. So starvation is another count and
boolean that the move() function has to keep track of to decide if it can breed() or not in the end. It also has to check the Ants in the adjacent Cells. If there is a single Ant, the bug moves to that index
. If there are multiple, the function adds them into a vector and randomly selects one. After choosing to eat an Ant, the bug deletes the Ant from the Grid.

- main.cpp creates the grid and prints the grid. The input values are defaulted at first. But we override the input values depending on the argc value.
This helps us override the given inputs in the command line and set the rest of the inputs to default regardless of how many inputs the user decides to give
as long as it does not exceed 7 (the max number of inputs expected)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

CITATIONS:

- We have decided to go slightly off the track and color code the ants and doodlebugs to make the output look more distinct.
We used an input in the Stack Overflow to call the ANSI Color codes:

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2616906/how-do-i-output-coloured-text-to-a-linux-terminal
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PROBLEM:

- The only problem we have faced was accidentally moving the Doodlebugs both in run() function which runs the whole simulation
and moving them again in the defined move() method in the Doodlebug.cpp
We fixed he issue after debugging for several hours.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HOW TO RUN THE PROGRAM:

- In the command line, type ./PA6 [gridSize] [numDoodlebugs] [numAnts] [steps] [seed] [pause]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

TESTING:
(WARNING: It is going to be a long testing log)
Did not use colored output for this log but the colors will show up on the terminal
Called command line: ./PA6
Defaults everything
